Its main holdings are with Susquehanna International Group, General Atlantic and Coatue Management. Three of bytedances sitting board members are US based, one is based in hong kong and one from singapore. No one on the board of directors is based in mainland china.2. The branches of bytedance which stores and makes decisions regarding tiktok and its user data are located in the US, Singapore and Ireland.Where tiktok is headquartered and operated. Data privacy concerns among tech companies are not exclusive to tiktok, but a federal ban of the application is.

I'm baffled by your description of TikTok - a bastion of small business owners, creative thinkers, harmless goofs, well-meaning humans just innocently connecting with other well-meaning humans. I don't know if it's because I'm an educator or a resident of a red state, but based on my experience, many of those (allegedly) mean and incorrect things that opponents of this tech monopoly have stated.....are just the actual truth. It's true that the McCarthyist conspiracy theorists are mostly full of bs. Concerns that unregulated social media can change global politics for the worse are completely justified though. It's happened multiple times. TikTok is also destroying the lives of young people - and by extension families, communities, the future etc. I've worked with multiple generations of kids, and sure, there is always grumbling about 'kids these days'..... but its never been like this. The majority of them don't have any sense of empathy or the work required to achieve goals (and I'm not talking kindergarteners, I'm talking 9-13 yr olds). If something is funny to them (bc they see it on many TTs), they'll do it, whether or not it actually harms a fellow human. If they see a school assignment as too hard/ not going to provide instant gratification (a la TT), they just won't do it. There are now millions of 12 yr olds who read at a 2nd grade level. And they don't give a crap. They believe they won't  need these skills to get a job -  they'll just be TT famous. Social media has permanently altered their brains for the worse. Without even going into the technicality of neurons and brain chemicals, just imagine a generation growing up without the ability to regulate their emotions, who don't even see the point of hard work and perseverance, who can't understand why it's not funny to punch someone, who are losing their ability to build/maintain relationships in person. I don't have to imagine any of that - I see it daily. That said, outright banning of problematic things hasn't proved very successful (the Prohibition, for one). I'm curious about what others have considered - a way forward that acknowledges the very real danger of doing  nothing about TT (and Facebook, for that matter) and the risk of being too punitive.

Tawny--First--I'm not a lawyer but my career has had me "dipping a toe in" legal issues for decades. so I think my opinion may be worth consideration.First--in the US we have a long history of letting industry "self-govern" until the industry (and the greed of the industrialists) becomes so obnoxious that it is exposed to the public who demand action.  If you think about it--"self-governing industries" brought us slavery. child labor, unsafe food and medicine, garment workers jumping to their deaths, the near extinction of the American bald eagle, and children's pajamas that caught on fire.  And rivers that caught on fire.    The majority of US legislators are too old to understand the technology, let alone how to go about regulating it to at least approximate the goals stated in your letter from the WH.Before addressing the "TikTok" problem, let me just say that I between the first TikTok hearings and the embarrassing conclusion one must reach--that Tom, Cotton either thinks Singapore is part of China or all Asians are secretly members of the CCP.--the Senate Rs have made giant asses out of themselves trying to force executives to answer "yes or no questions" that aren't actually yes or no questions  (and, had they gotten a "yes or no" they would have claimed as a lie).The point I need to make is that the government does have a daunting job of legally defining what is posted (press or private), where it fits within the 1A (which, like all amendments, is not absolute), determining and fighting out new laws and regulations, and then trying to defend them in the inevitable court cases.  A foreign owned platform may not be entitled to the same legal protections--I'm not sure. Unfortunately TikTok seems to be caught in this legal limbo.IMHO it seems like TikTok should create a wholly owned American subsidiary which states, in its incorporation paperwork, that there will be no managerial ties between the US and the home office except at the board level, that all American collected data will only be stored tn the US, and that all content will be somehow encrypted before transmission.   Agree to pay for the military to monitor content 24/7/365 until regulations are in place.It isn't fair--but it would probably be cheaper than fighting it out in the courts.
